AGI - The president of Botswana has threatened to transfer up to 20,000 elephants to Germany, irritated by Berlin's criticism of the hunt for pachyderms and the export of trophies of his country, which in his opinion aims to regulate the number of animals. The Germans must "live with animals trying to impose on us", said the leader of Botswana, Mokgweetsi Masi>, in comments to the German daily Bild published online today. "It's not a joke," he added about his offer to transfer 20,000 Pakistani to the North European country. "We would like to give this gift to Germany," said Masisi, adding that "will not accept a no as an answer."
&nbsp;
Botswana, a land of southern Africa without landslide on the sea, houses the largest population of elephants in the world, about 130,000, with whom cohabitation is often difficult, according to the president, referring to attacks on human beings, villages and crops. The German Ministry of Environment, managed by environmentalists, criticized elephant hunting trophies purchased by wealthy Western customers. At the beginning of this year, the ministry has advanced the possibility to put more stringent limits on the import of these trophies because of the problems of poaching. "We are discussing within the EU to extend the import authorization obligation (...) to other protected animal hunting trophies," said a ministry spokesman.
&nbsp;
Since Germany is one of the largest importers of hunting trophies in the EU, it has "a particular responsibility" in this sense, he added. As for the "regale" provided by President Masisi, the German Ministry of the Environment stated that " Botswana has not yet contacted" with him in this regard. In 2019, Botswana revoked the total ban on hunting, introduced five years earlier to reverse the decline of elephant populations and other species. The abolition of the ban has irritated the environmentalists. Commercial hunting is also an important source of local revenue. Since then, Botswana decides every year a share of animals that can be hunted. Last year the country offered 8,000 elephants to Angola and 500 to Mozambique by 2022.&nbsp;

